{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17476840","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17476840"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:52:40+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:52:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13956"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13956","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13956"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.68,0.06,0.2,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6586"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50091"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6586","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6586"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13956"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35370"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1172"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"1833"},{"type":"tags","id":"2453"},{"type":"tags","id":"2626"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4984"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"9278"},{"type":"tags","id":"11217"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13289"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41444"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44187"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50091","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/50091"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA six-year-old child presents to the Emergency Department with a two-day history of fever and progressive drowsiness. The child returned from a two-week holiday in Central Africa 14 days ago. There is no significant medical history, and the child takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, the child appears unwell. The pulse rate is 120/min, blood pressure 100/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 28/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 39.5\u00b0C. The child is comatose with a Glasgow Coma Scale score of 8. The spleen is palpable 2 cm below the costal margin. The liver is not enlarged.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations show:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin 120 g/L (135-205)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhite cell count 9 x 10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E/L (5.0-15.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPlatelet count 160 x 10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E/L (250-450)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESodium 137 mmol/L (135-146)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPotassium 3.8 mmol/L (3.5-5.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUrea 6.5 mmol/L (3.2-7.7)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECreatinine 60 \u03bcmol/L (40-80)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGlucose 2.4 mmol/L (2.5-7.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECSF glucose 3.5 mmol/L (\u0026gt;3.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECSF protein 1.0 g/L (\u0026lt;1.2)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Intracranial haemorrhage","Cerebral malaria","Bacterial meningitis","Dengue fever","Typhoid fever"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most likely diagnosis in this case is \u003Cstrong\u003Ecerebral malaria\u003C/strong\u003E. The child has recently returned from Central Africa, an endemic area for malaria, and presents with fever, coma, and splenomegaly. The blood tests show thrombocytopenia and hypoglycaemia, which are common findings in severe malaria. The CSF analysis is normal, which does not exclude cerebral malaria.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBacterial meningitis\u003C/strong\u003E is less likely given the normal CSF findings. Typically, bacterial meningitis would present with elevated CSF protein and decreased CSF glucose. Additionally, the white cell count is not elevated, which would be expected in bacterial meningitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDengue fever\u003C/strong\u003E could present with fever and thrombocytopenia, but severe neurological manifestations like coma are less common. Dengue shock syndrome can cause altered mental status, but other features like severe thrombocytopenia, liver enlargement, or signs of plasma leakage are typically present.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETyphoid fever\u003C/strong\u003E can cause fever and altered mental status, but the onset is usually more gradual. Relative bradycardia is often seen in typhoid, which is not the case here. While splenomegaly can occur in typhoid, the combination of coma and hypoglycaemia is more suggestive of cerebral malaria.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntracranial haemorrhage\u003C/strong\u003E could cause a decreased level of consciousness but would not explain the fever, splenomegaly, or laboratory abnormalities seen in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn a child presenting with fever and coma after returning from a malaria-endemic area, cerebral malaria should be high on the differential diagnosis. Urgent blood films for malaria parasites should be performed, and treatment should be initiated promptly if malaria is confirmed or strongly suspected.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cerebral malaria should be considered in febrile patients with recent travel to endemic areas.","Thrombocytopenia and hypoglycaemia are common findings in severe malaria.","Normal CSF findings do not exclude cerebral malaria."],"references":["White NJ, Breman JG. Malaria: Clinical manifestations and diagnosis in nonpregnant adults and children. In: UpToDate [online]. 2022. Available from: https://www.uptodate.com/contents/malaria-clinical-manifestations-and-diagnosis-in-nonpregnant-adults-and-children?search=malaria\u0026source=search_result\u0026selectedTitle=1%7E150\u0026usage_type=default\u0026display_rank=1","Idro R, Marsh K, John CC, Newton CRJ. Cerebral Malaria: Mechanisms of Brain Injury and Strategies for Improved Neurocognitive Outcome. Pediatric Research. 2010;68(4):267-74. Available at: https://www.nature.com/articles/pr2010173#citeas","Song X, Wei W, Cheng W, Zhu H, Wang W, Dong H, Li J. Cerebral malaria induced by plasmodium falciparum: clinical features, pathogenesis, diagnosis, and treatment. Front Cell Infect Microbiol. 2022 Jul 25;12:939532. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC9359465/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35370"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13956"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35370","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/35370"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-07T13:38:20+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-29T09:33:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6586"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50091"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"cre